About

There are interesting and consequential societal questions in the contemporary dialogue. It is hard to have a calm and fruitful conversation about these topics across the political division. The challenge stems partly from the emotional load and incompatible underlying assumptions and definitions associated with the phenomena.

The aim of these writings is to offer tools to structure thinking about the questions. The intention in most of the writings is not to guide the reader towards a certain political view, but rather to help improve understanding about the questions. In order to avoid shouting past each other in the public conversation, it is necessary to pinpoint first where the root of the disagreement lies.

A commonly accepted conceptual framework, a model in other words, can help us build a common ground for the conversation. A good model is flexible enough, so that it can be bent and twisted to accommodate different opposing views. The model can then be used to communicate thoughts more clearly, observe what follows from different underlying assumptions, and find out what kind of results to a societal change can be expected in different scenarios. Keep in mind the two famous quotes by Box “All models are wrong but some are useful” and Einstein “The model should be as simple as possible, but not simpler”.


What is a Woman?

February 2023

The concept of gender, what it is to be a man or a woman, has recently become a topic of public debate. Traditionally gender has been linked to sex - whether someone is biologically male or female. Some critics suggest that gender is more appropriately defined on the level of social behavioral patterns and norms, without the link to biology. The public conversation about the topic often fails painfully, when one side acts as if their favorite re-definition of gender has already been societally established, presenting statements like “men can get pregnant”, and the other side who still consider the words “man” and “male” to be synonymous can’t believe how someone could be so deranged. The aim of this article is threefold. 1) I propose a conceptual framework, which helps different sides of the argument avoid talking past each others. 2) I outline three possible pathways forward, of how to define or re-define gender. 3) The framework enables following through more clearly, what does the underlying assumptions regarding the biological connection between sex and gender, or lack thereof, entail for different suggestions moving forward.

Introduction

We create concepts (definitions and categories) to simplify the endless complexity of the world, in order to understand, communicate and function successfully in it. Most of our concepts are imperfect in the sense that they leave something relevant out, or overlap with other categories. Try providing an all-encompassing definition for the concept of “game”, for example?

The main justification for a category depends on its usefulness. Consider the Gregorian calendar, which is an imperfect categorization of time on planet Earth. It is imperfect in the sense that any discrete number of days doesn’t exactly match the time it takes for Earth to revolve around the Sun. A day has to be removed from the calendar on those years which are divisible by four but are not divisible by 100, unless they are also divisible by 400. Even this is not enough to make the calendar perfect, as unpredictable astronomical events impact the calendar, requiring ad hoc fixes in the long run. Regardless, having a common calendar which works most of the time is so useful that we accept it regardless of its epistemic imperfections.

In this article I argue that deciding what gender means is not a scientific problem, but a matter of definition. We posses the freedom to craft whatever definitions we please, although science can help us anticipate the usefulness of the suggested definitions.

The concept of sex is determined on the level of biology: A person with XY-chromosomes and small reproductive cells is a male, and a person with XX-chromosomes and large reproductive cells is a female. This categorization applies to most of the mammalian species, and most of the individuals within a species. There are some inter-sex humans, who don’t belong to either category, but they are very small in number. Because of its broad applicability, sex is considered a binary dichotomy.

Traditionally the defining character of gender has been biological sex: A woman is an adult human female and a man is the male counterpart.

Figure 1: raditionally the concept of gender has been attached to biological sex

Critics like Judith Butler point out that this is an incomplete description (Butler 1988). Much of what is considered “manly” or “appropriate for a woman” seems to relate to social patterns of behavior. Having male genitals is not enough to be considered a “real man” - it requires adequate success in performing the role of an ideal man. Hence, the biological sex seems to have only been the necessary but not sufficient condition in what makes a man or a woman.

Figure 2: According to Judith Butler, the concepts of man and woman mostly include social aspects. Biological sex has only been the necessary but not sufficient condition for gender, which it needn’t be anymore.

It is however not the case that social aspects have historically been a part of what determines the gender of a person in the West. Instead, these social roles have been criteria, based on which males and females have been judged as representatives of their biologically determined gender. If a male performed his role as a man inadequately, it impacted how much societal appreciation he garnered as a man, but not whether he was considered a man or a woman.

Every person has a mixture of feminine and masculine traits, emotional responses and behavioral tendencies. These social patterns are at least not directly determined by biological sex, which is evident from the variation of these traits within both sexes; there are for example plenty of feminine males and masculine females.

But in that case, is biological sex needed as the necessary or any kind of condition for the definition of gender?

Model of Sex and Gender

Consider the feminine-masculine -spectrum. It describes a simplified landscape of personality, social behavior, physical traits and emotional experiences. Every person has a unique mixture of feminine and masculine features, and thereby is located on that spectrum. The locations are drawn from the sex-specific probability distributions, \(X_{if} \sim \mathbb N(\mu_f, \sigma_f^2)\) and \(X_{im} \sim \mathbb N(\mu_m, \sigma_m^2)\), where \(i\in\{1,\dots,N\}\) and \(N_f=N_m=:N\), and the lower index \(g\in\{f,m\}\) in the mean \(\mu_g\) and variance \(\sigma_g^2\) denote for female and male sex, respectively.

let there be an ideal of a man \(\lambda_m\) and a woman \(\lambda_w\), to which every male and female, respectively, is compared to.

Figure 3: The concept of gender has been traditionally defined based on biological sex and every person’s worth is measured against an ideal of their gender. The female probability density curve of social traits is depicted in red and the male density curve in blue.

The sexes have been encouraged and pressured to act according to their respective gender roles. Men ought to be masculine, stoic and competitive, whereas women ought to be feminine, caring and motherly.

Failure to comply with the norms associated with one’s sex does not change the gender, but incurs social costs. In other words, the social characteristics of a male doesn’t impact what gender he is, but it defines whether he is considered successful as a man.

The closer a male is to the ideal man, \(|X_{im}-\lambda_m|\), the better of a man he is considered to be. An ideal is a motivator and a judge at the same time. The further a male falls short from the social demands of an ideal Man, the worse of a man he is considered to be. Likewise, a female who can’t or won’t perform the role of an ideal Woman, is deemed a lesser woman, but still a woman.

The aggregated discomfort with the traditional definition of gender and the ideals \(\lambda_f, \lambda_m\) can then be conceptualized for example in the following way \[\begin{align*} L &= \sum_{g\in\{f,m\}}\sum_{i=1}^N (X_{ig}-\lambda_g)^2 \end{align*}\]

This model is a simplification, as it is possible to exert strong feminine and masculine traits at the same time. The conceptual analysis can be extended by letting both masculine and feminine features vary freely, creating a two (or any) dimensional plane. This does not change the main results. The simplistic utility calculation above is not the be taken as a theory of human flourishment, but instead as one way to think about one aspect of a social topic.

Nature vs Nurture

An important and ethically relevant question arises: What would happen to the gender differences, if the social and cultural impact on human behavior was minimized, and only the biological impact would remain? In other words, what is the causal impact of biological sex on the behavioral patterns of a human, if any?

Let the means of the sex-specific behavioral distributions depend on the biological B and social influence S \[\begin{align*} \mu_f &= \alpha B_f + (1-\alpha) S_f \\ \mu_m &= \alpha B_m + (1-\alpha) S_m \end{align*}\]

where \(\alpha\in[0,1]\) issues the relative importance of the two factors.

Consider the two opposing hypotheses, where sex either has a strong or negligible impact on behavioral patterns.

Hypothesis 1: Strong nature position. Gender differences are strongly determined by biology, \(\alpha \approx 1\). Then, in the absence of social influence, the sexes would revert to their natural distributions of social patterns. The two distributions can still vary because of randomness, meaning that not everyone has to be identical with others of their sex even if gender differences were purely biological.

Figure 4: Under the strong nature position of hypothesis 1, the male and female social patterns differ also in the absence of social influence. The biological impact can be strong or weak, as in cases 1 and 2, respectively.

Hypothesis 2: Strong nurture position. Biology doesn’t influence behavior much at all \(\alpha \approx 0\). The gender roles mostly result from social construction and bare minimal biological connection to sex.

Figure 5: According to the strong nurture position of hypothesis 2, biological sex doesn’t predict gender identity at all. This could mean that humans are blank slates, case 1. It is also possible that people have behavioral proclivities driven by biology, but those proclivities are not based on sex, as in the case 2.

Under hypothesis 2, the gender roles \(S_f, S_m\) are socially constructed and it can be argued that there is no apparent reason to demand a specific sex to only function according to one of the gender patterns.

The analysis can be differentiated further. The sexes might have a different proclivity to respond to social pressure, \(\alpha_f \neq \alpha_m\). Both social and biological aspects might also impact the variance of the distributions \(\sigma_f^2, \sigma_m^2\). The gender boundaries can be socially constructed in any way, regardless of which hypothesis is closer to truth.

In real life it’s impossible to perfectly isolate only the biological influence for the human behavior. But this thought experiment can help us make predictions what we would expect to see, if we managed to move forward towards that kind of a world. It is also quite commonly accepted that humans are outcome of both nature and nurture, so neither hypothesis is likely to be true.

What to do?

“What is a woman?” is not a scientific question, it is a matter of definition. It is up to us as a society to decide how we wish to define the concepts we use. It would be perfectly coherent to define everyone with a brown hat as women and others as men. However, some concepts are more useful than others. Sciences can help anticipate how useful a new concept would be. For example, biology, sociology, psychology and other fields can shed light to the value of \(\alpha\), the relative share of influence from nature and nurture.

There are broadly three paths forward: Detach gender from sex, continue as before or change gender boundaries.

A. Detach gender from sex

Re-define gender on the social level, diminishing the role that the sex of a person plays in our cooperation.If the content of what defines a gender is mainly social and these traits vary within sexes, then upholding the link between sex and gender might alienate many.

Removing the link between gender and biological sex would then mean that a person who finds resonance with the role of a woman could declare to identify as that gender, regardless of the underlying biological sex. Under the Butlerian proposition, everybody is compared to that gender ideal that is closest to them, \(\lambda_W, \lambda_M\), the cost would become \[\begin{align*} L^B &= \sum_{g\in\{f,m\}}\sum_{i=1}^N (\min\{X_{ig}-\lambda_W, \ X_{ig}-\lambda_M\})^2 \end{align*}\]

It might be the case regardless of which hypothesis is closer to truth that the Butlerian definition reduces the societal discomfort stemming from rigid sex-based gender roles.

Gender doesn’t need to be a binary variable anymore, as it’s defined as a range on a continuum. Those who don’t fit into either of the gender categories could be characterized as non-binary or by defining new genders in this social space. The categories don’t have to be rigid either, they can take whatever form those identifying in the category choose to identify as. Consider a scenario, where k new genders and their ideals are designed to minimize the feeling of being an outsider for most of the people \[\begin{align} \min_{\lambda_1, \lambda_2 \dots \lambda_k} L^{B_k} &= \sum_{g\in\{f,m\}}\sum_{i=1}^N (\min\{X_{ig}-\lambda_1, \ X_{ig}-\lambda_2, \ \dots, \ X_{ig}-\lambda_k\})^2 \end{align}\]

One of the tradeoffs with this solution is that it becomes comically hard to answer basic questions like “what is a woman?”. Dismantling functional categories can also have all kind of secondary effects. For example, we need structure to function as human beings. Removing foundational structures can leave many people puzzled and lost.

B. Continue as before

Continue to uphold sex specific behavioral patterns and encourage individuals to pursue the roles that match their sex. This could be justified by claiming the usefulness of gender roles. Perhaps gender is a useful software on top of the hardware of sex, which the culture has managed to find over long search time of trial and error. The rather autistic utility calculations for the societal discomfort, \(L, L^B\) and \(L^{B_k}\), don’t say anything about the benefits of the gender categories for individuals and the society.

The notion that some aspects of gender are socially constructed does not mean that all of it is socially constructed. And even if something is socially constructed, it is not necessarily arbitrary, as there can be limitations to what kind of social constructs are possible or durable. Further, even an arbitrary social construct can be useful. Take for example the location of a pharmacy. It is not important where it is placed, the usefulness stems from it existing somewhere in the neighborhood - anywhere.

C. Change gender boundaries/ideals

The gender categories can be kept binary and sex-specific, but adjusted to accommodate more people. Modifying the model in Figure 3, suppose that instead of gender ideals there are regions on the level of social behavior for both genders. Inside of these regions all social performances are considered to be normal and acceptable for that gender. If someone is located outside of this region, they are frowned upon. Perhaps in the past these regions were too narrow.

Figure 6: Option C: Loosening the normative social requirements for genders allows more people to express themselves freely, without clashing into the boundaries of their gender.

After the broadening of social expectations, the gender categories now overlap, meaning that it is not considered unusual to have a masculine woman or a feminine man. The gender is still determined based on biological sex, but for most people it doesn’t restrict their ability to function in the way they resonate with.

The furthest we can go on this path is to widen the regions of acceptable gender to include most people. If hypothesis 1 holds true, we shouldn’t expect a drastic change - most males and females would still behave in much the same way as before the change in gender-norms. If hypothesis 2 is true, then the importance of biological sex would be expected to diminish because of its irrelevancy, in the same way as hair color or left or right -handedness.

Figure 7: Widening the gender categories to include all behavioral patterns, identically for men and women.

Another approach is to change the cultural gender ideals, by strengthening the social component S. Social movements and the entertainment industry tend to depict people in certain light. Casting females in masculine roles can be interpreted as an attempt to move the benchmark of ideal woman \(\lambda^w\) in the masculine direction towards the ideal man \(\lambda^m\).

Figure 8: Social programming can move the gender ideal of a woman into masculine direction, closer to that of a man, in the hopes that the female behavioral distribution will follow.

Under the nurture hypothesis, this would be expected to cause a shift in the social behavior towards the new ideal, for example females becoming less feminine and more masculine.

What would be the case if there was some truth in the nature hypothesis? If the new socially manufactured gender ideals are very different from the biological reality, it could increase aggregate discomfort. Females who still find themselves resonating with the feminine would feel estrangement for falling far from the new and more masculine ideal for women.

5. Conclusion

We are free to create and use whatever concepts we please. Some concepts are more useful than others. A categorization doesn’t have to be perfect in order to be useful. Science can in some cases help us rank the usefulness of competing categorizations, but can’t objectively help us pick one.

There is an ongoing debate regarding the need to re-define the concept of gender. More specifically, some critiques argue that biological sex is not needed in the definition of a gender identity, but rather it should harness its meaning solely on the social level of emotional and behavioral patterns. This opens up the possibility to craft new gender identities and make their criteria maluable. At the same time, it becomes comically hard to provide any meaningful definition of what it is to be a woman.

The aim of this article is to suggest a model for thinking the connection between sex and gender, or lack thereof. Using the model, I go through several options of how to proceed.

I suggest the Option C, where the definition of gender is kept tied to the biological sex, but the judgmental social pressure on how to perform the role of the given gender properly is loosened up, to leave more space for people to express themselves as they see fit, without the need to impose contrived changes to the linguistic domain.

References

Judith Butler (1989): Performative acts and gender constitution: An essay in phenomenology and feminist theory, Theatre journal, available (9/2023) on https://www.amherst.edu/system/files/media/1650/butler_performative_acts.pdf.


Trans-Women in Sports

June 2023

Introduction

A complication arises, if we accept the Butlerian separation of gender from sex: Should biological males identifying as women compete in women’s sports? Women’s sports is a protected class set up to increase the representation and possibilities of female athletes. Trans-women have gone through puberty as males, where the elevated testosterone accumulated them more muscle mass, stronger joints and tendons, and increased bone density, with respect to someone with a female puberty. In many sports this gives males an advantage over females, even if they lower their testosterone later on with pharmacological treatments.

But men and women are on many regards more similar than different, as there are larger differences within sexes than between the sexes. As a consequence, this also creates an unfair advantages for some individuals over others of the same sex. Does it therefore matter if a trans-woman has an advantage over some females, if the playing field is not level to begin with?

I demonstrate how even small differences in athletic prowess between an average male and female can lead to large differences between the male and female pro athletes. The consequence of this statistical property is that at the extreme, which pro sport is by definition, the male advantage is in many sports very large.

Differences exaggerate at the extreme

Consider a case, where an individual’s athletic prowess is drawn from sex-specific probability distributions, \(X_{if} \sim \mathbb{N}(\mu_f, \sigma_f^2)\) and \(X_{im} \sim \mathbb N(\mu_m, \sigma_m^2)\), where \(i\in\{1,\dots,N\}\), \(N_f=N_m\), \(\mu_m>\mu_f\) and \(\sigma_m>\sigma_f\), and \(\{f,m\}\) denote for female and male sex, respectively. An athlete is someone with an athletic prowess greater than 98 % of the sex. The male and female cutoffs for athletes are depicted by dashed lines in Figure below.

On the left a large overlap can be seen in the athletic ability between the male and female populations, but the gap widens on the right when only the top 2 % of males and females are compared.

Even small differences in expected values and variances between two largely overlapping populations (males and females) can translate into large differences at the extremes. There are many females who are stronger than many males, but for example at the elite level of powerlifting there are virtually no females who are stronger than any of the males. When it comes to combat sports, the stakes don’t only include winning and losing, but also potentially serious health consequences due to the mismatch.

If we were to abolish gender divisions and choose the best 2 % of the whole population as athletes, more than 97 % of the athletes selected would be males.

Therefore, it’s clear that under quite moderate assumptions, having gone through a male puberty gives a much stronger advantage in the women’s sports, than being a genetically exceptional female outlier.

What to do?

  1. Include trans-women in womens sports, which would be unfair to women.

  2. Create a separate class for trans-athletes, which would lead to very small participation numbers, hindering the excitement.

  3. Re-brand women’s sports as female sports. Then trans-men (females) who are on testosterone replacement therapy would have an unfair pharmacological advantage.

  4. Specify the protected category to be for female women only and create an open class for everyone else. This would be unfair to both trans women who typically have a medically lowered testosterone and trans men who lack the male puberty, both competing against male men. Regardless of the choice, someone has it unfair, especially trans-men athletes in most of the scenarios.

  5. Another way to approach the problem would be to abolish the gendered leagues althogether and come up with new metrics based on bone density, lean muscle mass, lung capacity or other relevant markers to craft fair and competitive leagues for different sports. This might be impractical and leave female athletes with a lesser spotlight, as demonstrated in the second simulation above.


Can We Reduce the Number of Incels?

March 2023

Introduction

There is a group of males who live in involuntary celibacy (incels), without being able to fulfill the human desires of having sex, being touched, or feeling accepted. For some people this predicament can continue for years, driving them deeper into isolation, resentment and in rare cases even into violence.

There are two competing hypotheses explaining the emergence of the incel phenomenon. The quality hypothesis underline the lack of attractive qualities in the incels, and the rank hypothesis focuses on the changing norms on the mating market. The crucial difference between these approaches boils down to the underlying core issue: How do men and women choose sexual partners?

Quality hypothesis: Assume that men and women both only consider a candidate partner’s perceived level of quality when choosing a short term mate, and not at all how the candidate compares to other candidates. Then it seems that the predicament of incel men must result from their lack of social and emotional skills, hygiene, success and because of their misogynistic worldview. Perhaps their lack of female attraction is a consequence of, rather than the reason for their personal shortcomings and resentful misogynistic ideology. If only these particular incel men would improve their shortcomings adequately, the whole incel phenomenon would vanish, and almost no one would be left in long term celibacy against their wishes.

Rank hypothesis: Now consider the possibility that particularly females not only consider the quality, but also the rank of the candidate on the male hierarchy; How does the candidate compare to other males? This mating strategy is called hypergamy in the sociological literature. It is then possible that the incel phenomenon was born as a consequence of a shift in social norms governing sexual behavior. More specifically, 1) sex was detached from the marriage and it was no longer required to occur only under monogamous social arrangement. A new sexual marketplace emerged, which set free 2) the hypergamous mating habits of females, i.e. the tendency on average to choose partners who are higher than them in the socioeconomic ranking, and 3) the promiscuous mating habits of males, making those with options capitalize on the overflow of female attention. This combination allows females to pick and share higher quality mates, without someone’s luck being another one’s loss. For males, this creates a highly unequal Pareto distribution of success with regard to the female company. The rank of a male is expected to influence the female choice with an unknown weight \(\alpha \in [0,1]\) relative to the quality of the male.

In this article I take an agnostic view on what holds true, and instead consider the societal impact of the following intervention under both hypotheses: The quality of every current incel man is improved at least up to the level of the first non-incel man. If the quality hypothesis holds true, this should fix the problem. But if the rank hypothesis is correct, even if all current incels improved their relevant qualities and ended their celibacy by the intervention, the new bottom of the male hierarchy would then be cast into involuntary celibacy.

Before continuing, it is important to bear in mind that acknowledging a phenomenon doesn’t have any connection to moral judgements about the phenomenon.

Model

Every person has a level of quality, referring to their social and emotional skills, personal hygiene, earning prospects, physical attributes, intelligence etc. The absolute qualities of men and women are drawn from normal distributions \[\begin{align*} Q_{im} \sim \mathbb N(1,0.4) \\ Q_{iw} \sim \mathbb N(1,0.2) \end{align*}\]

where lower index i stand for the individuals \(i \in N^m, i \in N^w\), m and w denote the gender of the individual, and \(N^m=N^w=:N\) is the population size of the given gender.

The quality distribution of both sexes has the same expected value, but the male population is more variable than the female population, meaning that it produces more outliers in good and bad.

This quality determines the likelihood of an individual meeting other people. For example, someone with good social skills and attractive face might end up on more dates than than someone lacking on those respects.

Everyone also has a relative ranking within their gender, \(R_{im}, R_{iw}=\{1,2,\dots N\}\), defined by the rank order of their quality \(Q_{im}, Q_{iw}\). This rank impacts the chances of a meeting leading to a match only under the rank hypothesis.

The absolute qualities are used to define an NxN meeting matrix M with a likelihood for a meeting between every possible pair of men and women \(M=Q_{m}Q_{w}^T\), with T denoting for a transpose.

Absolute qualities and meeting likelihoods of men and women

Quality hypothesis: The actual number of sexual or romantic encounters \(S_{ig}, g\in\{m,w\}\) for every man and woman only depends on their absolute qualities. It can be calculated as the sum of the row/column of M, or equivalently as \[\begin{align*} S_{im}^b &= \gamma*Q_{im} \sum_{j = 1}^{N} Q_{jw} \\ S_{iw}^b &= \gamma*Q_{iw} \sum_{j = 1}^{N} Q_{jm} \end{align*}\]

where the success parameter \(\gamma>0\) describes the fraction of meetings that lead to a romantic encounter.

In this scenario there are 0.6 % of the population with less than one match, who are incels by definition. All of them are men.

Rank hypothesis: The number of sexual partners of women only depend on their absolute qualities, as before. But for men it also depends on their relative rank \(R_{im}\) on the male hierarchy. \[\begin{align*} S_{im}^h &= \gamma*\left[ Q_{im} \sum_{j = 1}^{N} Q_{jw} \right]^\alpha \left[\frac{(2R_{im})^2}{\alpha N^2}\right]^{1-\alpha}\\ S_{iw}^h &= S_{iw}^1*D \end{align*}\]

where \(\alpha\in(0,1]\) controls how important the male rank is for women and \(D=\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{S_{im}^h}{S_{im}^b}\) distributes the change in the number of encounters, relative to the case under quality hypothesis, equally for all women. The particular functional form is arbitrary and only serves the function of making the rank count for the female mating choice.

I will compare four cases, \(\alpha\in \{1, 0.75, 0.5, 0.25\}\), where the first one corresponds to the Baseline.

The histograms describe the distributions of the number of partners for men (blue) and women (red) in four scenarios, where only the women’s mating proclivities differ. When the hypergamous tendency of women increases, the male hierarchy becomes Pareto-distributed, with some very successful men and many with barely no success. The dashed line at 1 partner gives the incel-cutoff.

Intervention

Consider an intervention, which improves the absolute qualities \(Q\) of every incel from the worst scenario (\(\alpha=0.25\), with 9.3 % incels), at least up to the same level of the first non-incel. This would include improving their job status, physical attractiveness and social skills, but also making their worldview potentially less resentful.

Results

Quality hypothesis: The incel problem is successfully eradicated, as all men now meet the absolute standard that is demanded by women. The amount of sexual encounters increase for both sexes.

Rank hypothesis, cases 2-4: The impact of the intervention on the share of incels diminishes sharply, when hypergamous tendency increases (smaller \(\alpha\)). The remaining incel-population does not necessarily compose of the same individuals as before. If the rank hypothesis holds true even partly, then the incel phenomenon can’t be solved by only improving the absolute qualities of men. There will always be a bottom x %, regardless of how the population is shuffled. Any specific man doesn’t have to be an incel, but someone will be.

In this article I considered the impact of a perfect intervention, in which every current incel man is made more attractive to women, at least up to the standard that women currently demand. These men land jobs, become more hygienic, less misogynistic, more fit and develop better social and emotional skills. Many commentators have suggested a weaker variant of this intervention as a solution to the incel problem.

We find out that this intervention is very effective, if it is the case that women only choose their partners based on their absolute qualities. However, if women also take the relative status of the candidate in the male hierarchy into account, then the intervention has only a limited impact.

Traditionally the incel problem was solved by socially upholding the norm of monogamy, by allowing sex to only take place within a marriage. This restrained both female hypergamy and male promiscuity, creating a sexual socialism of sort.

It is not certain what ought to be done to the incel problem, if anything. Whichever hypotheses holds true, the best strategy for any individual person, incels included, is to focus on personal responsibility and try their best. But on a societal level, it is important to do cost-benefit analysis for different social contracts and to understand the impact of underlying assumptions on the effectiveness of potential policy choices. If the rank hypothesis describes the behavior of even a subset of women, it might mean that the incel phenomenon is unsolvable in our current social culture. In that case the deprivement of the incel men can be accepted as a necessary cost of upholding the spirit of the sexual revolution and hookup-culture. But it would then seem cruel not to extend at least some sympathy for them.

The problem with modern dating

November 2023

Modern technology has brought millions of possible sexual and romantic partners available in principle to everyone. With the cost of an airplane ticket, you could meet basically anyone in the world. Actually there’s no need to even move, as dating apps bring everyone to you. Consider the aim of finding a life companion to start a family with. How should this one person be chosen out of all potential candidates? Before two people get to know each other properly, there’s a lack of information about their compatibility. One solution is to engage in dating, which reveals the information about the compatibility of the couple. The couple can then either break up and continue the search, or make the choice to end searching and build a life together.

Due to severe limitations, it is not possible to go through every possible partner candidate and choose the best afterwards. Romantic relationships are very expensive institutions, which require a lot of emotional bandwidth, time and effort. They also exert path dependency neurologically by launching a storm of addictive brain chemicals, and psychologically by establishing a status quo which can be hard to challenge. Even at best, there’s only a handful of people we can dive into a relationship with, before having to commit the final choice, if you want kids. What is needed is a filtering algorithm, which selects prospective romantic partners out of the pool of potential candidates.

How should we, then, choose the small subset of all actual partners from among the potential ones? The prevailing strategy of the modern dating market seems sub-par. Here is the strategy in pseudocode:

  1. Choose a domain: Bar or tinder
  2. Choose a candidate based on sexual attraction and vibe
  3. Move fast to sex. If sex is good enough, continue dating, but keep looking at the same time
  4. Slowly find out about characteristics of secondary importance: Music taste, hobbies
  5. If nothing too horrible comes out, begin a monogamous relationship
  6. Hang out until some fundamental difference in values or goals manifests and break up
  7. Immediately continue the same procedure from step 1 onwards

Let’s go through the reasons, why this is an inefficient algorithm given the goal of starting a family, akin to trying to find home with a random walk. Needless to say, the following is my private take.

Step 1. Problem with the typical domains in modern dating is twofold: Alcohol and lack of information. Meeting new people often includes alcohol, which reduces the ability to think and make good choices. Getting to know someone for an hour or two in a dark, noisy club while being drunk, and then going to a sealed private space alone with them for sexual purposes is a recipe for disaster. Any psychopathic narcissist can masqerade as a catch for that long. It is wise for especially women but also for men to avoid combining alcohol and sex. If you find someone attractive at a night club with the prospect of sex, just exchange numbers and see if you both still want to meet the next day sober. If the date leads to sex then, nothing was lost abstaining in the previous night. If not, then it was probably better that way.

Many dating apps also reveal very little information about the prospective candidates. It would be better to meet people organically and get to know them as people first, before asking them out. The framework for meeting people should be chosen to maximize the chances of meeting suitable people, such as social events related to university, gym, library, hobbies, etc. But alas, it is not possible for all busy professionals to organically meet enough people, so online dating might have to do.

Step 2. Many people consult their feelings religiously. We are not talking about deep emotions like love yet at this stage, but instead of surface level feels. These feelings are not objective, stable and all-encompassing truths. Many people know that their feelings can sometimes be misleading. For example, it’s possible to find someone attractive, with whom a harmonious and synergic future would evidently be impossible. Feelings should be amalgamated with reason to create a powerful intuition for introspection and foresight. Reason allows simulating how the future might look like with different potential candidates. These scenarios can then be evaluated by thinking how it would feel to find oneself in them. Both feelings and reason can reveal different type of deal breakers, while being blind to others. Relying on just one of them is doomed to fail.

Steps 3-5 are completely backwards. It would be more useful to introduce monogamy early on and instead delay sex. Delaying sex for some weeks or even months postpones the immolation of the storm of brain chemicals, which can momentarily override reason and skew emotions. It’s hard to evaluate whether you’re on the correct path, if you can’t see it in the fog. If the partner is actually prospective for a life companion, there’s no rush. If not, the absense of sex also makes it easier to call off the relationship.

Monogamy allows the two to really concentrate in getting to know each other seriously, without making the situation unnecessarily complicated and hurtful via unuseful hedonistic multitasking. I find it autistic and sociopathic to deal with monogamy as a contractual matter, introduction of which to a romantic danting relationship depends on what is popular in the culture at the moment. When you find a real prospect, omit others for the time being. If you don’t have a real prospect at hand, don’t engage in dating.

A counter argument arises: “There is not enough time to only date one at a time.” Firstly, The barrier to engage in a romantic relationship should be higher than “(s)he seems cute”. It doesn’t seem plausible that multiple real prospects for a life companion would emerge simultaneously. Quality over quantity. Secondly, not much time needs to be dispensed in the process either. With an open and honest communication, mature adults should get an intuition about the long term prospect of the potential relationship: If it would probably end anyway after the chemical storm has past in a couple years, then it should be ended right away. It is the noisy filter, poor focus and hedonism which end up wasting time.

Speak more! It never seizes to amaze me how people entangle themselves in a web of misunderstandings, false expectations and unnecessary disappointments, just because they fail to communicate openly. It’s ok to only want sex in a committed relationship and its ok to want it casually, but these two should not mix due to miscommunication (setting lying aside). Instead of tiptoeing around hard topics, the compatibility should be deliberately tested by seeking to engage in conversations regarding all of the deep and important subjects. The sooner a possible dealbreaker comes up for either one, the better. You should want your partner to accept you as you really are. Amazingly, some people only find out after years that their preference for having kids differs from their partners’.

Step 6 misplaces the burden of proof. The relationship should not continue just because everything is ok. This is one of the most exclusive and important choices of life. Treating a relationship as a placeholder to dispel insecurity or boredom would make it a very expensive hobby. It is also un-romantic if the choice to be with someone stems mainly from ones inability to be alone and generic need for someone. I find the idea much more romantic that you would generally not want to be with anyone, but feel like you can’t choose otherwise when it comes to me in particular.

Sometimes people only worry about the suffering that breaking up would cause. But not breaking up is also a choice with hidden costs, which can materialize later on more intensely. In retrospect, feeling that you lost years with someone, having to start all over from the beginning again, might dim also some of the happy memories. If you’re unsure, then make an effort to find out. If you can’t reach clarity, then its probably not meant to be.

The importance of shared values and aims can’t be emphasized enough. If the foundation of relationship is harmonious, then there is less need to compromise and bicker. It doesn’t help if two people like the same music, if their differing worldviews constantly drive them to clash. Small differences in important stuff can accumulate over the time, whereas even larger differences in secondary issues can be overcome under the sympathy of souls.

Step 7, finally, tries to avoid and compensate the pain with short term pleasures. There is an understandable urge to fill the emptiness with whatever relief is available. However, in this state of mind the choice of new partners is likely arbitrary and doesn’t reflect real preferences. This is probably not good for neither of the parties. It is also somewhat bleek to run into someone else’s arms right after a breakup. Like going to a strip-club to find whatever comfort directly after a funeral. It might be honorable for the past relationship and your own psyche to take enough time off for mourning and reflection to neutralize, before continuing the search.

Here is an algorithm that tries to fix the aforementioned problems:

  1. Choose a domain: Library, university, gym, hobbies, social events
  2. Choose a candidate based on mutual values and aims in life
  3. Slow down! Get to know them properly in a neutral setting. Focus just on them - monogamy from early on. Talk a lot, be honest and demand the same from them. Cover most relevant hard topics. After having strong evdence about the deeper compatibility, consider the sexual attraction.
  4. Introduce the sexual aspect to the relationship when you have enough evidence on the long term compatibility
  5. Find actively out the rest of the important issues related to compatibility. It is desirable that if there is something unacceptable, both find it out sooner than later. Also have fun. Being serious about dating doesn’t necessitate dating feeling like work.
  6. Make the decision, one way or another. If you’re still undecided after a couple of years, break up.
  7. After a break-up, take time to just be alone. Process the feelings and reflect. A lot. Only when you’re normalized, open up to the possibility of a new partner.
